ronomical Soc\niety. i- a prominent figure in the field\nof astronomical srlence. For ten year*j\nho has been profeeror of astronomy\n:\u00ab\u2019id director \u00ab.f the observatory at\nl\u2019rlncrton University. He was born\nnt Oyster Bay, where his father wan\nfur so\\ oral wars Theodor*' Roosevelt*!*\nt actor. He if- rUrd Ills A. 15. at\nPrinceton in 1537 an I continued his\ntudier; tit Cambridge University. His\nfi; t professional work was as a re\nir> h i i la nt for the i 'urnrcir In\n:'t:i* i\u2022\u00bbn n t Washington. Recently\nProfovsor Ru-cell has attained a\nworld-w do repuiation in astronomical\ncircle-. thru it is theory of stellar evo\nlution.\nTODAY\u2019S ANNIVERSARIES\nfl'- Daniel V. i: An her, one of whose\noperas brought **n a revolution,\nborn nt i.'acn, France. Died i n\nParis. May J 3, IST I.\nJBZI ounte-s of Mbanv. who married\nthe port Alfirl. tiled at Florence\nIh\u00bbrn September 27. 1788.\nParliament of Ganada unani\nmously resolved an adhcaion to\nthe toother country.\n1596 Maine* body <>f Cuban insurgent\narmy defeated. with heavy loss,\nat St. Lucia.\nIV*C Andrew t'arnegie ga\\f* JtO.OOh.ooo\nto the trustees of t h*- Carnegie\nInstitution at Washington.\n1306\u2014Airship \"California Arrow\" flew\n4\u25a0> miles at I#o* Angeles.\n1911\u2014The Duke of Connaught was ap\npointed to succeed Earl Gray aa\nGovernor-General of Canada\n-191- President Wilson vetoed the In\nmigration bUI.\nONE YEAR AGO TODAY\nOne hundred and seventy thousand\nworkers in the employ of the United\nStates Corporation received a 10 per\ncent advanco in wages.\nTODAY\u2019S BIRTHDAYS\nDuke of the Abruxzl, celebrated nr\ntraveler, explorer and naval command\nrr. born 18 years ago today.\nPr. V. K. Wellington Koo, lafe\nChinese minister at Washington, now\nminister to Great Britain, born in\nSlia ugh;\u2022 33 yeai lod#:\nDavid Murray. It. famous\nlandscape painter, born in Glasgow.\nScotland. 72 years ago today.\nJared T. Sanders, former governor of\nI/ouislanii. born in St. Mary Parish,\nLouisiana, 62 years ago today.\nKoJI Yfttnadn. eelebratod Japanrs.\nprofessional billiard player, born In\nTokio, S 3 years ago today.\nBlshef. Aria.\u2014Six boys brought re\ncently Int** Juvenile court on minor of\nf noses were rentenecri to remain a way\nfrom the movies for mt month- Tim\npolice chief \u00bb.r Instructed lo :rr that\nu.c untenoi wu cnforCt L 1\nDeath Penalty for Bootleggers\nIn a recent editorial The Manufacturers\u2019 Record\ncalls attention to the fart that the bootleggers them\nselves arc establishing a penalty for violators of the\nVolstead law more rigorous than any I hat legislators\nhave dared to inflict.\nAny person who engages in the outlawed business\nof poisoning his fellow man for- profit, and thereby\nestablishes himself as a criminal under the laws of the\nland, is not likely to be scrupulous in his discrimination\nbetween poisons of various sorts. If grain alcohol is\nnot to be bad wood alcohol is usually obtainable, and\ntbr* victim of the additional fraud involved in substi\ntuting one for the other is not usually in a position to\nmake effective complaint.\nIn the old days of the open saloon there were many\nbarkeepers who never swallowed the intoxicants they\nserved out to others. There is even greater reason for\nsimilar abstention on the part of the bool loggers, as\notherwise opposition to prohibition may shortly fail be\ncause of the extermination of those who are making it\ntheir business to break Ibis law.\nBigger and Better Than Ever\nA little cyclopedia of Colorado\u2019s progress and .re\nsources is the proper name for the annual edition of the\nDenver and Rio Grande\u2019s Red Book, which is usually\npublished in January. This year the publication con\ntains 392 pages, and it is made up for the most part of\nshort articles concerning Colorado industries, resources,\naccomplishments and opportunities, written hv men and\nwomen who arc recognized as authorities in their par\nticular lines.\nThe industrial and recreational attractions of Pu\neblo arc well presented in an article by Secretary Gray\nof thapPucblo Commerce Club, and other districts of the\nArkansas valley, the San Luis, the San Juan and the\nWestern Slope arc given full prominence.\nSpecial attention is given this year to Colorado\u2019s\ngreat infant industry, oil shale, while sugar heels and\nthe tourists also receive due recognition.\nThe Denver and Rio Grande railroad company sel\ndom tnisscs an opportunity to prove both its ability and\nits willingness to cret hack into its old position as a front\nrank promoter of Colorado prosperity, and Colorado peo\nple generally would be delighted to see the Rio Grande\nofficials free once more to do the things they would like\nto do for this state.\nOne Form of Bribery\nThe outcry that is made against Representative\nPonfcr\u2019s bill, prohibiting pledges by legislative candi\ndates in return for promises of support in their cam\npaigns, is sufficient proof of the need of sonic measure\nof this kind.\nIt is true that the people have a right to know the\ncandidate\u2019s opinions upon matters \u00ab\u00bbf current political\ninterest, and the bill under discussion very wisely dis\ntinguishes between such statements and positive pledges\nto perform particular legislative acts.\nThere is small chance that the Pcntor bill will be\ncome a law, for there arc too many }*eoplc in the state\nwith special interests of various kinds who. make a\npractice of tying candidates\u2019 hands in advance. P.*it\nthe bill is right in principle, just the same.\nWanted \u2014A Leader\nDebating societies in search of a good subject. con\ncernin': which much may he said on both without\nconclusive results, might well consider the proposition\nthat no other Democratic candidate for president could\nhave been so thoroly defeated as was James M. C\u00bbs in\nilast November election.\nIrrespective, however, of whether the Ohio states\nman is better qualified to play the role of Democratic\nMoses or of Democratic .Jonah, the fact remains that he\n!is*nndrr a sort of obligation to* retain the responsibility\nof Democratic leadership, at least for the time neces\nsary to make the November verdict effective and to\ntransform the party of administration into the parly of\nopposition.\nQUESTIONS AND ANSWERS\n(Any reader can get the an\nswer to liny question by writing\nTbe Pueblo Chieftain Information\nBureau. Frederic J. Ilaakln, Di\nrector. Washington, I>. C. Tbia\noffer on plies strictly to informa\ntion. rhe bureau ennnot give ad\nvice on legal, medical nnd finan\ncial matters. It does not attempt\nto nettle domestic troubles, nor to\nundertake exhaustive research on\nany subject. Write your question\npin Inly and briefly. Give full\nname nnd address and enoJoae\ntwo rents In cramp* for rctana\nl>osiagc. All replies are sent di\nrect to the Inquirer.)\nQ What part of tho human body\nis water? E. C. D.\nA.- Water forms over 60 per rent of\nthe weight of the body of the average\nman.\nq. Why Is New York called\n[Gotham? F. H. V.\nA- The term \"Gotham\" Is applied\nito New York aatlrlcally. The allusion\nif. t.. a parish by this name in England\nt rioted for tho simplicity Of its inhub\nitanti In the 16th century a collection\nof I'.rir;* s-ald |o l*r by Dr. Andrew\nBordn i made about, them including\nthr\u00bb hymn about tho \"Three Wise Men\n*if Gotham.\" Tho term was first u.-*d\nbv Washington Irving in \"Salmagundi'\nin 1807.\nQ. I am ending you n post card\nshowing carriages on Rotten Row. You\nsay only the king can drive thr.rcon.\nHow about it? Englishwoman.\nA. -Tho post card shown both Rol\nlon Row. which is ;l bridle path, and\nthe driveway which runs beside it.\nQ A llttl. girl from Pittsburg wants\nto know why m> many places In South\nern Florida, urn ailed Key. Ilk** Key\nWes*. fun you tell her? A. .1. S.\nA The word \"key\u201d ns applied to\ni chain *.f i.l.md *.fT iho Florida\ncoaat, i dcri cd from liio Span lull\nTHE PVEBIO CHIEFTAIN\nThat Governor Cox has small liking for the job\nthus thrust upon him. is evident, and his reluctance ii\nnot removed by his knowledge that at some future time\nthe Republicans will probably, thru dissensions or folly,\ngive t.ho Democrats another chance. The latest Demo*\nemtio candidate is not,\u2014to put the matter simply,\u2014 a\nstatesman of tho Bryan type, who would be content to\nremain in the political wilderness for forty years, if\nthereby lie might retain bis partisan pre-eminence and\nentertain Chautauqua audiences with the stories of his\nexperiences.\nA prominent Denver banker, who recently returned\ntr*Sni a business trip to eastern cities, is quoted in a\nnewspaper interview ns saying: \u2018\u2018The territory served\nby the Denver branch of the federal reserve bank of\nKansas City, which inc ludes Colorado and northern New\nMexico, appears to be in a very favorable position as\ncompared with some other parts of the country. In\nfact, this is one of the bright spots in the United States\nso far as financial conditions are concerned. While\nmoney has been tighter in this section than in the past\ndecade yet our condition lias been easy as compared\nwith the deplorable conditions in certain other sections\nof the country.\nWhat is true in a general way of this region, is true\nin even creator degree of the Arkansas valley and es\npecially of the city of Pueblo, In fact it may be truth\nfully said that hard times, so far as Pueblo is concern\ned, is merely the echo of something that is going on\nelsewhere and not at all something that is happening\nin our own city.\nIt. is well that the people of Pueblo and of Colorado\nhould keep these facts in mind, for otherwise they may\neasily think themselves into a condition of doubt and\ndepression for which there is no reasonable basis. And\nas eastern business experts are unanimously agreed that\nthe period of depression is already nearing an end and\nthat the full tide of prosperity caunot be delayed more\nthan a few weeks, it would be supremely foolish for\nColorado people to worn.' themselves with a belief of\nhard times that never were, just at the time when the\nplaces t hat had really been thru depression are rejoicing\nin the return of prosperity.\nManufacturer./ Record.\nIndicative of the upward trend in industrial, muni\ncipal and housing developments in various sections of\nthe South tiro tho many reports from railroads, muni\ncipalities. industrial corporations, building and loan as\nsociations. good-reads, commissions and similar bodies,\noutlining th* expansions planned for 1921. as published\nin the columns <*f the Manufacturers Record this week.\nProminent among these announcements is the expendi\nture of 118.000.uu0 in extensions and improvements by\nthe Norfolk A- Western Railroad; the development of it l\ni 100-mil* system of good roads in Georgia, some of\nwhieh is complete and the remainder In courso of ron\nruction, at a total cost of more than 17.500.000. i:on\nstructiun of 390 miles of highways in Mississippi, partly\ncomplete, entailing a cost of (t. 000.000; tho launching\nof l*lg programs tor municipal Improvement* in many\n\u00ab\u2019itics iii th*' South, together with Increased activities in\nindustrial and building development, as indicated by the\nincreased \\olunic <\u00bbf permits issued during th*- first few*\nweeks of the n mv year: the bringing in of oil wells in\nnew fields in Texas and Arkansas, and the optimistic\nspirit revived In textile mill centers as a result of the\nplacing of new orders of substantial size permitting the\noperation of quite a number of mills at full time.\nOil developments f considerable magnitude are\nnow transpiring. Last week u unique well wa.s brought\n:n near Fort Stockton, Tex., with an initial flow of 200\nbarrels an hour at 96 feet, and finally settled down to\n400 barrels dally.\nUnion county. Arkansas', dream of oil has become a.\nrealty with Hie bringing in of a 1 \".000-barrcl daily oil\ngusher near Eldorado.\nBuilding activities continue to increase, as indicated\nby tlie number of permits issue.l during the first two\nweeks of the new year, and urefilled* and contractors\nin the various states report that early spring will kto\nthe inauguration of a big industrial and lonising pro\ngram More than 3 1.280.000 %\\ill hr expended in Nor\nfolk this year upon streets, sidewalks, sewer* and similar\nImprovements following the completion of a BJ.ooo.oot*\nprogram In 192\". If half of the projected construction\nproject- are started thin year in Mobile. Ala., it Is said\nthat tho city will experience on*- of tin* most active\nbuilding year n its history. Winston-Salem has pin\nployed a Pittsburgh firm to draft a dtv plan to relievo\ncongestion on the downtown streets and \u00bbnigge.-t needed\ncity improvement:* of all kinds. A sanatorium nt El\nPaso. Tex., is being erected ut a cost, of I joo.nni*. n*\nports from Wheeling. W. Va.. show that a number of th*-\nsteel mills and similar plants in the territory. are operat\ning at or near capuclty, with work in for many\nmonths.\nGood-road* Improvement#* continue to be pushed\nvigorously in the various states, and effort* are being\nmade to make available bond Issues voted some tin***\nago but held nt* because of high prices for material'*\nand labor and the low prices offered for the b**nd-\nword \"Cayo\u201d, which means a low\nInland. The term is used In regions\nwhere t\u00bb\u00ab*\u2022 Spanish language Is or was\nformerly used.\nQ. \u2014What is tlie difference in ve\nlocity between tli\u00ab* incoming and out\ngoing tide.; in the Golden Gate? P.\nA. H.\nA. Tho hydrographic office of\nnavy says that the, inward tides of\nGolden Gate ha\\ c a velocity of 3.3\nknots and th* outward of 3.4 knot:.\nmaking a difference of 1 of a knot in j\nthe voice It j between the Incoming\nand outgoing tides of that port.\nQ. \u2014Will butter made **f sweet\ncrivim keep better limn th which\nis mad*' from sour cream? I. M. C.\nA Th*- department of agriculture\nways that butter made of sweet cream\ndoes keep better. Butter mode of\nunrlpone.d or sweet cream 1* specllled\nin orders from tho United Slates navy\nfor tills reason.\n(J. How much Iro should a farmer\nharvccl for his summer use? F. It.\nA. Tl*. department of agriculture\nsays that it is estimated that two ton*,\nto each cow In the herd will allow\nfor melting and leave enough for\nfamily need- Where cream only\nsold, about one-third of the quantity\no< '\u2019in bi needed\n<j. Arc buffaloes becoming extinct\nin ill s country 11. It. A\nA. At one time there whs a real\nuiger 11*.* I th* buffalo would dii ij*\npear entirely. In 1908 there wero but\n1116 will and tame buffaloes in the\nUnited States. Sine* l then, attention\nhas been given to tho situation, and\ntin: American Bison society reports\nthat this number bad Increased to\n3,39.1 In 1920.\nG. -Why Is tho Union Jark so\ncalled? A. 2*l. P.\nA. King Janies 1 \u00ab>f England\nsigned lik nntno .luck or Jacques, tlm\nFrench for James. In 1606 this king\nordered i Joint det let to bi used ft\nth ro al flag i Britain and cir\ncumstance gavo Uio name of tho flag.\nColorado\u2019s Prosperity\nSouthern Prosperity\nRAW MATERAL\nBY OPTIMO\n\"All work and no play makes Jack a\ndull boy\" litis proverb applies to\ncities, too.\nCities like men. {fascinated by th'\nwhirl of the wheels of Industry, often\nforget that a Utile relaxation from th*\nhard grind is not a* waste of time, but\nrather a period \u2022*f replenishment.\nThe youth of Pueblo is ailing to\nyou.\nPueblo r-hould have a hundred tennis\ncourts; a dozen base ball diamonds\nscattered thniotil the city would help\nt-. make boys manly, and keep men I\nyouthful.\nWhat diversion does your son or j\ndaughter have after school hours? j\nTlie Boy S*out movement Is n great\nstep towards the solution of tho 1\nyounger boy problem; tin* Y. M. C. A.\nis doing a wonderful work for all boy*,\n.inti all men; the Y. \\V. t\u2019. A. lias at\nheurt th*- interests of the young\nv omen. But. tlie citizens of any city\nmust assist these good Influences.\nPut before th** youth of the city\nmore t*. good, than there\nare temptations lo bn*l.\nGive tin' boys and girl* a chance\nDon\u2019t let your youth envy tlie\nyoungster In th* other it> make him\nhappy here by gl\\ing him the oppor\ntunity for the healthful recreation he\nso sorely ii cod* and desires.\nAnd you too, .Mr. Business Man you\nare the fellow who must guide tlie\ndestinies of this city a few years more\n\u2014keep yourself fit!\nWhy can\u2019t wo turn a hundred \u00ab*f\nthese vacant lots Into useful, health\ngiving courts, and add z**st to the\nsport by having city tournaments?\nIt\u2019s worth a thought, people.\nBargain week in used cur al the Hil\nler State Auto Co., 9th and Main.\nHoroscope\n\"The St nr a larHae,\nBat Do Not Compel.\nSATURDAY, JANUARY 20, 1921\nCopyright. 1921. by the McClure\nNewspaper Syndicate.)\nAstrologers read this as rather an\nunimportant day in planetary direc\ntion. Early in the* morning Mercury\nis in benctic aspect and later both\nJupiter and Saturn aro friendly. In\nthe evening Uranus i 3 strongly ad\nverse.\nTho early hours of this day are es\npecially auspicious for tho pushing of\npublicity or advertising, both of\nwhich should bo unusually profltablo\nin the new year.\nLeases and contracts signed today\n.should ho satisfactory in a financial\nway and should assure pleasant asso\nciations.\nAuthors have the forecast of a year\nin which extraordinary opportunities\ncome to them. Dramatists should\nbenefit especially.\nThere is a promising sign for trade\nand commerce, also for building,\nwhieh should be very\u2019 active in tho\nspring.\nThe evening of this day is especial\nly unfortunate for love affaire. De\nception is made easy by the sinister\naspect of Uranus.\nWomen should b\u00ab- exceedingly care\nful in all their business dealings un\nder i his sway, whieh may incline\nthem to take too many risks.\nThe sun benefits railways and poflt\noffleo affairs ut this time. Many\nchanges are foreshadowed.\nSickness of nn epidemic character\nseems to I*o foreshadowed for the late\n\"inter, Sanitation should bo watched\ncarefully.\nThe death of a noted clergyman, or\nscholar is presaged by the stars. A\nfamous scientist will suffer a mortal\nillness next month.\nThe position of Neptune threatens\nscandals in high life, and one of the*\"'\nwill touch a man in official placo in\nthe west.\nMercury is in an aspect that dr\nnotes much wind during th*' winter\nand early spring. Destructive, storms\nat sea are indicated.\nPersons whose birthday It is should\nkeep the health in order and con\nserve nervous energy. Business may\nrequire attention. Fa!so friends may\ncause trouble.\nChildren born on this day may be\nexceedingly bright and enterprising\nSuccess in financial enterprises is\nforetold.\nTODAY\u2019S EVENTS\nToday is Carnation Day, the annual\nmemorial day to tho lato ITcsident\nMcKinley.\nKansas today will celebrate the six\ntieth anniversary of its admission to\nthe Union.\nThe Rt. Rev John J. Twiwler today\ncompletes his fifth year as bishop of\nthe Catholic dioceso of Ix-ad. South\nI Dakota.\nI Beginning today and continuing\n[thru the coming -rrk a great carnival\njof winter sports is to l\u00bbe held at\nRaniff, Alberta.\nThe annual National Sportsmen\u2019s\nshow ui!i open today In Madison\nSquare Garden, New York, to conttnuo\nthru the coming week.\nWHY\nla A \u201cPHA.YCKUOR\u201d M\u00bb YAUKDf\n(Copyright. 1920. By The Wheeler\nSyndicate, Inc.)\nEven when wo find that the title\n\"\u00ab\u2019hancellor\" is derived from th* 1-itin\ncancellus. a grating whieh is also\nthe root-word nf \u00bb\u00bbur vert* \"to cancel'\u2019\nit is still puzzling to trace the con\nnection between a lattice-work and tlie\noffice \u00ab*f Ixml High Chancellor **r the\nchancellor of the Exchequer. But the\napplication of the name and the grad\nual evoution of thr office came about\nin this manner:\noriginally. In the Roman I-Tmplre. a\n\u2022\u2019chancellor\" was a petty ofilcer sta\ntioned at the fence or lattice-work of\nn law court In order to see that unau\nthorized persons did not pass this\nboundary line. Th\u00ab- Emperor Carl nun.\nthe immediate predecessor of Diocle\ntian, caused a great deal of adverse\ncriticism thruout tho Empire by ap\npointing a \"chancellor\" t** the office\nof Prefect or Rome. Later. In the\nEastern Empire, a \"chancellor\u2019\u2019 was a\nsecretary who sat inside the lattice\nwork and who was also invested with\njudicial functions, and. ultimately.\nv\\Hh the work of over-seeing the other\nofficer* of the Empire. I-'rom this high\ndignity t\" that of an English lx*r*l\nGhano\u2019cllor is only a simple step, hut !t\nis Interesting to note that thruout this\nentire process of evoluion, tlie name\ngained from the proximity of tlie lat\ntice-liars of the court should have per\nsisted to tho present day.\nMonday WHY I* John Bull\u201d the\nnational figure of England?\nThe Romance of Words\n\u201cnoo 1\nCopyright. 1!t20. B? Tlir NVhcclcr\nSyndicate, In**.\nOne or the most Interesting point. 1\nwhich strikes the Investigator of lan\npin|[o as he digs back into the ante\ncedents of words in common use today.\n1; the part played by clothing in con\nnection with different terms and the\nimportance which wearing apparel ns-\nMimed by reason of its Indicating rank\nand position. 11s well as because of\nits Intrinsic value. Wo read, for ex\nample. that the man who fell among\nthieves on his way from Jerusalem\nto Jericho was \u201cstripped of his rai\nment\u201d. and that the meager and piti\nful clothing worn by t'hrlst was di\nvided by I\u00ab\u00bbt among the Roman sol\ndiers who carried out tho sentence of\ncrucifixion.\nMere, therefore, we have pictures of\nboth the modern and ancient applica\ntion of the word \"mb\", which comes\nfrom the Old French robbo or robe\nmeaning a loak. while its ori